# Descriptive Analysis
import pandas as pd

# Frequency counts for each countrys top genres
genre_counts_by_country = df.groupby("Country")["Top Genre"].value_counts().unstack(fill_value=0)

# Add row percentages (within each country)
genre_pct_by_country = genre_counts_by_country.div(genre_counts_by_country.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100

# Display counts and percentages
print("=== Frequency Counts ===")
display(genre_counts_by_country)

print("\n=== Percentages by Country (%) ===")
display(genre_pct_by_country.round(1))

# Get top and least popular genre per country
top_genres = genre_counts_by_country.idxmax(axis=1)
least_genres = genre_counts_by_country.idxmin(axis=1)

genre_summary = pd.DataFrame({
    "Top Genre": top_genres,
    "Least Genre": least_genres
})

print("\n=== Top & Least Popular Genre per Country ===")
display(genre_summary)

### Platform Preference Trends
### Question: Which streaming platforms are most used in different age groups or countries?
### Analysis: Grouped bar plots, pie charts, clustering by usage.
In[23]:
# Descriptive Statistics for Platform Preference

# 1. Overall counts
platform_counts = df["Streaming Platform"].value_counts()
print("Overall Platform Counts:\n", platform_counts, "\n")

# 2. Proportions
platform_props = df["Streaming Platform"].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
print("Overall Platform Percentages:\n", platform_props.round(1), "\n")

# 3. By Age Group
platform_counts_by_age = (
    df.groupby("Age Group", observed=False)["Streaming Platform"]
      .value_counts()
      .unstack(fill_value=0)
)
print("Platform Counts by Age Group:\n", platform_counts_by_age, "\n")

# 4. By Country
platform_counts_by_country = (
    df.groupby("Country", observed=False)["Streaming Platform"]
      .value_counts()
      .unstack(fill_value=0)
)
print("Platform Counts by Country:\n", platform_counts_by_country, "\n")

# 5. Normalized proportions (easier comparison across groups)
platform_props_by_age = platform_counts_by_age.div(platform_counts_by_age.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100
print("Platform Percentages by Age Group:\n", platform_props_by_age.round(1), "\n")

platform_props_by_country = platform_counts_by_country.div(platform_counts_by_country.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100
print("Platform Percentages by Country:\n", platform_props_by_country.round(1), "\n")

# Statistical Test (T-Test) (Free vs Premium, if only two groups)
free = df[df["Subscription Type"]=="Free"]
premium = df[df["Subscription Type"]=="Premium"]

for metric in metrics:
    t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(free[metric], premium[metric], equal_var=False)  
    print(f"{metric}: t={t_stat:.2f}, p={p_val:.4f}")

Minutes Streamed Per Day: t=0.14, p=0.8886
Discover Weekly Engagement (%): t=0.87, p=0.3848
Repeat Song Rate (%): t=1.25, p=0.2125
In[47]:
# ANOVA Test (is >2 subscription types, free, student, premium)
for metric in metrics:
    groups = [group[metric].dropna() for name, group in df.groupby("Subscription Type")]
    f_stat, p_val = f_oneway(*groups)
    print(f"{metric}: F={f_stat:.2f}, p={p_val:.4f}")

# 3. Country Specific Popularity
# Function to plot top N artists for a given country
def plot_top_artists(country, n=10):
    artists = df[df["Country"]==country]["Most Played Artist"].value_counts().head(n)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    sns.barplot(
        x=artists.values,
        y=artists.index,
        hue=artists.index,      # use y as hue  no FutureWarning
        palette="mako",
        legend=False
    )
    plt.title(f"Top {n} Artists in {country}")
    plt.xlabel("Number of Listeners")
    plt.ylabel("Artist")
    plt.show()

# Generate plots for each country
plot_top_artists("USA")
plot_top_artists("UK")
plot_top_artists("Japan")
plot_top_artists("India")
plot_top_artists("Germany")
plot_top_artists("France")
plot_top_artists("Canada")
plot_top_artists("Brazil")
plot_top_artists("Australia")

# 1. Simple Regression (Minutes  Songs Liked)
import statsmodels.api as sm

X = df["Minutes Streamed Per Day"]
y = df["Number of Songs Liked"]

X = sm.add_constant(X)  # add intercept
model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()

### Segmentation of Users
### Question: Can we segment listeners into groups (e.g., casual, engaged, heavy users)?
### Analysis: Clustering (K-means), PCA for dimensionality reduction, segment profiling.
In[115]:
# Prepare data for clustering
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Select engagement features
features = df[["Minutes Streamed Per Day", 
               "Number of Songs Liked", 
               "Repeat Song Rate (%)", 
               "Discover Weekly Engagement (%)"]]

# Handle missing values (if any)
features = features.dropna()

# Standardize features (important for clustering)
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(features)
In[110]:
# K-means cluster

# Choose number of clusters (lets try 3: casual, engaged, heavy)
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)
df["User Segment"] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

In[113]:
# Optimal Number of Clusters (Elbow Method)
inertia = []
for k in range(2,8):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    km.fit(X_scaled)
    inertia.append(km.inertia_)

plt.plot(range(2,8), inertia, marker="o")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("Inertia")
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal Clusters")
plt.show()
